            <div id="docText">
                <div id="be-doc-text"><p>ADVENTURE and danger have run throughout Richard Tomlinson's life
but his decision to reveal the names of more than 100 spies has been
his biggest gamble yet.</p>
<p>It was in 1991 that Tomlinson decided to swap his comfortable,
well paid job as a City management consultant for espionage. It
meant a pay cut for the maverick, but he felt this would be more
than
compensated by the intrigue of life in the Secret Intelligence
Service, MI6.</p><p>Tomlinson was a high-flier at Cambridge University, graduating
with a double first. His taste for adventure was evident as an
undergraduate when he crossed the Sahara on a motorbike and joined
the Territorial Army SAS.
He became bored with life in the City and in 1991, at 27, he was
recruited to MI6. &hellip; </p></div>
                
            </div>
            
